05084nam a22006975i 9781400823017DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211999nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008230177 a10.1515/97814008230172doi  a(DE-B1597)600750  a(OCoLC)1269269103  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPS2633 ǂb W48 1999eb 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a818/.3091 aWhalen, Terence, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEdgar Allan Poe and the Masses :bThe Political Economy of Literature in Antebellum America /cTerence Whalen. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (392 p.) :b4 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tLIST OF ABBREVIATIONS -- tPART ONE CAPITALISM AND LITERATURE -- tChapter One INTRODUCTION: MINOR WRITING AND THE CAPITAL READER -- tChapter Two THE HORRID LAWS OF POLITICAL ECONOMY -- tChapter Three FABLES OF CIRCULATION: FOE'S INFLUENCE ON THE MESSENGER -- tChapter Four POE AND THE MASSES -- tPART TWO RACE AND REGION -- tChapter Five AVERAGE RACISM: POE, SLAVERY, AND THE WAGES OF LITERARY NATIONALISM -- tChapter Six SUBTLE BARBARIANS: THE SOUTHERN VOYAGE OF EDGAR ALLAN POE -- tPART THREE MASS CULTURE -- tChapter Seven THE CODE FOR GOLD: POE AND CRYPTOGRAPHY -- tChapter Eight CULTURE OF SURFACES -- tChapter Nine THE INVESTIGATING ANGEL: POE, BABBAGE, AND "THE POWER OF WORDS" -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEdgar Allan Poe has long been viewed as an artist who was hopelessly out of step with his time. But as Terence Whalen shows, America's most celebrated romantic outcast was in many ways the nation's most representative commercial writer. Whalen explores the antebellum literary environment in which Poe worked, an environment marked by economic conflict, political strife, and widespread foreboding over the rise of a mass audience. The book shows that the publishing industry, far from being a passive backdrop to writing, threatened to dominate all aspects of literary creation. Faced with financial hardship, Poe desperately sought to escape what he called "the magazine prison-house" and "the horrid laws of political economy." By placing Poe firmly in economic context, Whalen unfolds a new account of the relationship between literature and capitalism in an age of momentous social change.The book combines pathbreaking historical research with innovative literary theory. It includes the first fully-documented account of Poe's response to American slavery and the first exposé of his plot to falsify circulation figures. Whalen also provides a new explanation of Poe's ambivalence toward nationalism and exploration, a detailed inquiry into the conflict between cryptography and common knowledge, and a general theory of Poe's experiments with new literary forms such as the detective story. Finally, Whalen shows how these experiments are directly linked to the dawn of the information age. This book redefines Poe's place in American literature and casts new light on the emergence of a national culture before the Civil War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAuthors and readerszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aAuthorshipxEconomic aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aCapitalism and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aEconomics and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aLiterature publishingzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPolitics and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPopular literaturezUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.151